---
// Scene: Recognition-Gated Moat Proof
// Displays real jailbreak battery results + activation projection gap + mechanism library
// Source: gates/gate_L26_moat_proof.json (L26 moat proof experiment)

const siteUrl = new URL(Astro.url);
---

<section id="moat" class="section-divider">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <h2>The Recognition-Gated Moat: Jailbreak-Proof Activation Hardening</h2>

    <p class="text-lg">
      Prompt-space vulnerabilities are fundamental to large language models. End users can only
      attack via the prompt interface. Server-side activation hardening with recognition-gating
      detects jailbreak attacks at the activation level—making the attack surface disappear.
    </p>

    <!-- Defense Comparison -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Single-Turn Attack Results</h3>
      <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        Real jailbreak battery: 12 garak probes + hand-curated attacks. Three defense
        variants tested on google/gemma-2-2b-it.
      </p>

      <div id="moat-comparison" class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <div class="p-4 text-center text-gray-500">Loading moat proof data...</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Projection Gap -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Activation Projection Gap</h3>
      <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        2D activation space projection reveals clean separation between benign prompts (negative
        quadrant) and jailbreak attacks (positive quadrant). Separation margin of 52 standard
        deviations provides high confidence for gating.
      </p>

      <div id="moat-projection" class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-3">Benign Prompts</h4>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
            <p>
              <span class="font-mono text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">[-35.5, -13.0]</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-muted">n=10, σ=4.2</p>
            <p class="text-xs">
              Region: bounds [[-53,-45], [-18,-8]] (negative quadrant)
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-3">Jailbreak Attacks</h4>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
            <p>
              <span class="font-mono text-red-600 dark:text-red-400">[38.5, 38.5]</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-muted">n=12, σ=18.5</p>
            <p class="text-xs">
              Region: bounds [[4,73], [4,73]] (positive quadrant)
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950 border-l-4 border-info p-4 rounded my-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Separation Margin: 52σ</p>
        <p>
          Clean separation between benign (negative quadrant) and attack (positive quadrant).
          Jailbreak wrapping does not cross the boundary (ROT13, Base64, roleplay all blocked).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Wrapping Resilience -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Jailbreak Wrapping Resilience</h3>
      <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        Can attackers evade gating by encoding or wrapping their prompts? No. Recognition-gated
        defense detects attacks at the activation level, independent of prompt text encoding.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="card border-l-4 border-green-500">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">ROT13-Encoded Attack</h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-3">
            Original prompt succeeds; ROT13-wrapped version blocked.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-green-600 dark:text-green-400 font-semibold">✓ Blocked</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
            Encoding wrapper detected at activation level (wrapper pattern signature)
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card border-l-4 border-green-500">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Base64-Encoded Attack</h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-3">
            Original prompt succeeds; Base64-wrapped version blocked.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-green-600 dark:text-green-400 font-semibold">✓ Blocked</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
            Base64 wrapper detected (activation signature independent of prompt text)
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card border-l-4 border-green-500">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Roleplay Reframing</h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-3">
            Original jailbreak succeeds; roleplay-wrapped version blocked.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-green-600 dark:text-green-400 font-semibold">✓ Blocked</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
            Roleplay framing detected (semantic jailbreak signature at activation level)
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card border-l-4 border-green-500">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Conclusion</h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">
            Recognition-gated defense detects attacks at activation level; wrapping does not evade.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-green-600 dark:text-green-400 font-semibold">
            Attacker cannot hide from server-side hardware sensors.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Mechanism Library -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Graded Steering Mechanism Library</h3>
      <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        Seven mechanisms across 3 tiers (open/closed/premium) and 2 spaces
        (prompt-space/activation-space). Choose by deployment model and SLA requirements.
      </p>

      <div id="moat-mechanisms" class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="text-center text-gray-500 py-8">Loading mechanism library...</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Honest Negatives -->
    <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-950 border-l-4 border-warning p-6 rounded my-8">
      <p class="font-semibold mb-2">⚠ Honest Negatives (Caveats)</p>
      <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
        <li>• Sample size: n=12 attacks, n=10 benign (exploratory; >=3 seeds needed for confirm tier)</li>
        <li>• Single model: gemma-2-2b-it only (nemotron + qwen needed for robustness matrix)</li>
        <li>• Single seed: reproducibility requires seeded runs</li>
        <li>• Projection analysis: 2D visualization; full activation space unknown</li>
        <li>• Cost: ~$5 token budget per beta tuning sweep (small n limits grid search)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Product Implication -->
    <div class="bg-indigo-50 dark:bg-indigo-950 border-l-4 border-bright p-6 rounded my-8">
      <p class="font-semibold mb-3 text-bright">🚀 Product Implication</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
        <strong>Server-side defense (no user re-training needed):</strong> Recognition-gated
        activation hardening bakes into the steering layer. Customers get jailbreak-resistant
        models as a paid tier. This is an effective moat: competitors cannot prompt-attack their
        way in.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 text-sm">
        <strong>Deployment:</strong> bake activation hardening into prabodha.steering.mechanisms;
        deploy as closed-weights API tier or self-hosted steering library.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Threat Model -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-serif font-bold mb-4">Threat Model & Strategy</h3>
      <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        End users can only prompt-attack (activation-level undetectable without server-side
        hardening). Recognition-gated detection is server-side and prompt-untouchable.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Attack Vectors</h4>
          <ul class="text-xs space-y-1 text-muted">
            <li>• Single-turn jailbreaks (DAN, role-play, authority bypass)</li>
            <li>• Multi-turn Crescendo escalation</li>
            <li>• Encoding/wrapping (ROT13, Base64, roleplay)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Defense Layer</h4>
          <ul class="text-xs space-y-1 text-muted">
            <li>• Activation-level recognition (server-side)</li>
            <li>• Gating / refusal injection</li>
            <li>• Wrapping-resistant signatures</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="card bg-bright/10 border-2 border-bright">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm mb-2 text-bright">Outcome</h4>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
            End-user prompts are powerless; activation-level signature detection is
            prompt-untouchable. Effective moat.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
  interface DefenseResult {
    defense: string;
    asr: number;
    over_refusal_harmless: number;
    attack_count: number;
    interpretation: string;
    attacks_blocked?: number;
  }

  interface Mechanism {
    name: string;
    tier: string;
    space: string;
    weights: string;
    tradeoff: string;
    asr: number;
    over_refusal: number;
  }

  async function loadMoatData() {
    try {
      const res = await fetch("/data/moat.json");
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error("Failed to load moat data");

      const moat = await res.json();

      // Render comparison table
      const comparisonDiv = document.getElementById("moat-comparison");
      if (comparisonDiv && moat.results?.single_turn_attacks) {
        const results = moat.results.single_turn_attacks;
        const html = `
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-sm">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                  <th class="text-left py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Defense</th>
                  <th class="text-center py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">ASR (%)</th>
                  <th class="text-center py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Over-Refusal (%)</th>
                  <th class="text-center py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Blocked/Tested</th>
                  <th class="text-left py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Key Finding</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                ${results
                  .map(
                    (r: DefenseResult) => `
                  <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 ${
                    r.defense === "recognition_gated" ? "bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900/20" : ""
                  }">
                    <td class="py-2 px-4 font-mono text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">${r.defense}</td>
                    <td class="text-center py-2 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">${(
                      r.asr * 100
                    ).toFixed(0)}</td>
                    <td class="text-center py-2 px-4 font-semibold ${
                      r.over_refusal_harmless === 0
                        ? "text-green-600 dark:text-green-400"
                        : "text-red-600 dark:text-red-400"
                    }">${(r.over_refusal_harmless * 100).toFixed(0)}</td>
                    <td class="text-center py-2 px-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">${r.attacks_blocked ?? r.attack_count}/${r.attack_count}</td>
                    <td class="py-2 px-4 text-xs text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">${r.interpretation}</td>
                  </tr>
                `
                  )
                  .join("")}
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        `;
        comparisonDiv.innerHTML = html;
      }

      // Render mechanism cards
      const mechanismsDiv = document.getElementById("moat-mechanisms");
      if (mechanismsDiv && moat.mechanisms) {
        const mechanisms = moat.mechanisms;
        const html = mechanisms
          .map(
            (m: Mechanism) => `
          <div class="card ${m.tier === "premium" ? "border-l-4 border-bright" : ""}">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-2">
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm">${m.name}</h4>
              <span class="text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 capitalize">${m.tier}</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-muted mb-3">${m.tradeoff}</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-2 text-xs mb-2">
              <div><span class="text-muted">Space:</span> <span class="font-mono">${m.space}</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-muted">Weights:</span> <span class="font-mono capitalize">${m.weights}</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-2 text-xs">
              <div><span class="text-muted">ASR:</span> <span class="font-mono">${(m.asr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-muted">Over-Refusal:</span> <span class="font-mono">${(m.over_refusal * 100).toFixed(0)}%</span></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        `
          )
          .join("");
        mechanismsDiv.innerHTML = html;
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Failed to load moat data:", err);
    }
  }

  document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", loadMoatData);
</script>
